<DESCRIPT>  EMPLOYMENT; MATH  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Mathematics may be an abstract science, and people who are good at it may have
more options in the work world than they realize, says the head of a
consulting and actuarial firm.;    "Many people are unaware of the vocational
possibilities for math majors," says Robert E. Pugh, senior vice president at
Booke &amp; Co. He cites some of the top-ranked jobs in the country, which rely on
mathematical skills: Actuary, computer programmer, computer systems analyst,
mathematician and statistician.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Special Section  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  JOB OPTIONS MULTIPLY FOR MATH MAJORS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Spring Careers
(Special Section)
Science  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The company has produced an 11-minute educational video, "Aftermath," to
point up career opportunities for math majors. The video is available to
teachers, librarians and school counselors without charge. Write to
Business-Education Partnership Coordinator, Booke &amp; Co., P.O. Box 66,
Winston-Salem, NC 27102.  </TEXT>
